00:06:32,670 --> 00:06:36,400
wanted to make sure I talked about, what examples, who I talk to,

140
00:06:36,400 --> 00:06:37,830
expertise, and so forth.

141
00:06:37,830 --> 00:06:42,680
It's got enough information, but not so much that it's visually cluttering.

142
00:06:42,680 --> 00:06:46,570
So let's say finally, note cards aren't going to do it.

143
00:06:46,570 --> 00:06:47,910
The outline's insufficient.

144
00:06:47,910 --> 00:06:50,910
And you actually need to deliver a manuscript speech.

145
00:06:50,910 --> 00:06:54,550
That's going to happen on occasion, for whatever reason you have to do it.

146
00:06:54,550 --> 00:06:57,300
Again, make sure the script works for you.

147
00:06:57,300 --> 00:07:02,670
And how you wrote it in your word processing program, or how it might

148
00:07:02,670 --> 00:07:06,780
appear if you were going to hand it out to someone in paragraph form is

149
00:07:06,780 --> 00:07:10,670
probably not how you want to make that manuscript for oral performance.

150
00:07:10,670 --> 00:07:13,070
So you're probably going to be using a bigger font.

151
00:07:13,070 --> 00:07:15,900
There's probably going to be more spacing.

152
00:07:15,900 --> 00:07:19,300
Just like with the note cards, I want to put in a card turn where there's a

153
00:07:19,300 --> 00:07:21,440
natural break in the presentation.

154
00:07:21,440 --> 00:07:26,500
I want to make sure that my paragraph breaks or my pause breaks are coming

155
00:07:26,500 --> 00:07:28,030
when I'm going to be turning a page.

156
00:07:28,030 --> 00:07:31,150
I don't want to write it so I'm turning a page mid-sentence.

157
00:07:31,150 --> 00:07:32,860
That's just bad planning.

158
00:07:32,860 --> 00:07:37,140
So I just want to make sure that I'm using this in a way where the page

159
00:07:37,140 --> 00:07:42,240
turn I have to do any way is going to fall in a place that I want to be

160
00:07:42,240 --> 00:07:43,360
putting a pause.

161
00:07:43,360 --> 00:07:48,560
And then as I'm formatting that document, I probably want to focus on

162
00:07:48,560 --> 00:07:50,020
phrasing groups.

163
00:07:50,020 --> 00:07:54,190
So what do I want to say as a phrase rather than on paragraphs?

164
00:07:54,190 --> 00:07:55,930
I probably wrote it in paragraphs.

165
00:07:55,930 --> 00:07:59,330
But then I go through, and I'm breaking out those paragraphs based on

166
00:07:59,330 --> 00:08:01,810
what are the phrases I want to deliver.

167
00:08:01,810 --> 00:08:05,570
So what you end up with is something that doesn't look like a series of

168
00:08:05,570 --> 00:08:06,560
paragraphs.

169
00:08:06,560 --> 00:08:07,210
You can see here.

170
00:08:07,210 --> 00:08:10,960
This is a manuscript speech I did not too long ago.

171
00:08:10,960 --> 00:08:16,150
So you see I've got lines that are really aimed at that's what I'm going

172
00:08:16,150 --> 00:08:21,500
to perform, that chunk of talk, that sentence or two sentences

173
00:08:21,500 --> 00:08:22,810
is a chunk of talk.

174
00:08:22,810 --> 00:08:24,510
And I want to deliver it as a chunk.

175
00:08:24,510 --> 00:08:28,730
The big breaks, the drop downs, are between these phrase groups.

176
00:08:28,730 --> 00:08:32,650
I want to put in lots of those so I can find my place on the page quickly

177
00:08:32,650 --> 00:08:34,640
and easily.

178
00:08:34,640 --> 00:08:41,140
So however you plan on using notes, you want to make sure that they're

179
00:08:41,140 --> 00:08:45,960
going to help you in that performance, be it note cards, outlines, or a

180
00:08:45,960 --> 00:08:47,470
manuscript.

181
00:08:47,470 --> 00:08:49,680
Make sure you've chosen the right one for the occasion.

182
00:08:49,680 --> 00:08:52,510
If it's an extemporaneous setting, reading a manuscript

183
00:08:52,510 --> 00:08:53,980
isn't going to work.

184
00:08:53,980 --> 00:08:57,010
So you want to make sure you've chosen the appropriate mechanism.

185
00:08:57,010 --> 00:09:02,470
For these informative speeches, for this class, I'd recommend either note

186
00:09:02,470 --> 00:09:07,900
cards or that outline model, certainly not manuscripts for these speeches.

187
00:09:07,900 --> 00:09:11,240
Whatever you choose, practice with it.

188
00:09:11,240 --> 00:09:16,050
I am shocked how many times I see people practicing their speech,

189
00:09:16,050 --> 00:09:19,320
working on their speech, and then making their notes five minutes before

190
00:09:19,320 --> 00:09:20,900
they go deliver the speech.

191
00:09:20,900 --> 00:09:22,580
Man, that's a recipe for failure.

192
00:09:22,580 --> 00:09:27,270
Because those note cards are going to be your lifeboat the second you stand

193
00:09:27,270 --> 00:09:28,230
up to speak.

194
00:09:28,230 --> 00:09:30,640
You wouldn't quickly patch together a--

195
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:31,580
that metaphor doesn't work.

196
00:09:31,580 --> 00:09:34,930
If the ship were sinking, you would patch together a lifeboat as quickly

197
00:09:34,930 --> 00:09:35,960
as you could.

198
00:09:35,960 --> 00:09:39,710
In performance of a speech, you want to spend some time thinking about, how

199
00:09:39,710 --> 00:09:42,020
is this actually going to shape your performance?

200
00:09:42,020 --> 00:09:44,100
No one ever needs to see your notes but you.

201
00:09:44,100 --> 00:09:45,740
So make them useful.

202
00:09:45,740 --> 00:09:49,110
And the way you're going to make them useful is by practicing with them,

203
00:09:49,110 --> 00:09:52,930
figuring out if it's awkward to use in your notes.

204
00:09:52,930 --> 00:09:56,400
Make sure that they're accessible and easy to use.

205
00:09:56,400 --> 00:10:00,390
And let me just conclude with one final point.

206
00:10:00,390 --> 00:10:06,620
Be it note cards, or a manuscript, be kind to your notes.

207
00:10:06,620 --> 00:10:11,680
Often, you'll see people delivering their speech, and they're nervous.

208
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:13,820
And so their mangling their notes.

209
00:10:13,820 --> 00:10:16,020
The notes didn't do you no harm.

210
00:10:16,020 --> 00:10:17,490
Be kind to those notes.

211
00:10:17,490 --> 00:10:20,070
And so too with your manuscript.

212
00:10:20,070 --> 00:10:21,840
If you've got a manuscript and a podium, great.

213
00:10:21,840 --> 00:10:23,090
Keep it there.

214
00:10:23,090 --> 00:10:25,040
Reference it, but keep your hands free.

215
00:10:25,040 --> 00:10:30,290
You know, you're not in the point of getting ready to swat a fly with it.

216
00:10:30,290 --> 00:10:32,220
Don't be mean to your notes.

217
00:10:32,220 --> 00:10:32,980
They're there to help you.

218
00:10:32,980 --> 00:10:34,260
They're your friend.

219
00:10:34,260 --> 00:10:35,920
Don't beat them up and be mean to them.

220
00:10:35,920 --> 00:10:37,730
So practice with those notes.

221
00:10:37,730 --> 00:10:39,120
Plan those notes.

222
00:10:39,120 --> 00:10:41,330
And with that, improve your performance.

223
00:10:41,330 --> 00:10:45,890
And don't be that guy from week three, who only at the moment of speaking

224
00:10:45,890 --> 00:10:49,680
learned that his notes we're preparing him only for disaster.

